# Glossary

> Each term includes **definition â†’ guitar-specific note â†’ example**.  
> For deeper exploration, click **â†’ Learn more** to jump to Music Theory.

---

## A. Fundamentals

### Scale Degree
**Definition**: **Numbers 1â€“7** within a key. **1 = tonic**.  
**Guitar Note**: When the key changes, "1 (tonic)" moves (= movable do). Number relationships stay constant.  
**Example**: In C major, 1â€“2â€“3 is **Câ€“Dâ€“E**. In D major, it's **Dâ€“Eâ€“F#**.  
â†’ Learn more: [/resources/music-theory#degrees](/resources/music-theory#degrees)

### Interval
**Definition**: Distance between two notes (perfect 5th, minor 3rd, etc.). Independent of key.  
**Guitar Note**: Use **degrees for progressions/melodies**, **intervals for voicings**.  
**Example**: Power chord = **1 (root) + 5th**.

### Key
**Definition**: The tonal center and pitch level of a piece.  
**Guitar Note**: **Key selection** determines 80% of singability. Capo comes after.  
**Example**: Chorus too high â†’ try half-step down (â€“1).  
â†’ Learn more: [/resources/music-theory#key-roman](/resources/music-theory#key-roman)

### Diatonic
**Definition**: The "core members" of a key.  
**Guitar Note**: Build the skeleton with diatonic chords first to avoid confusion.  
**Example**: D major diatonic chords: **D Em F#m G A Bm C#Â°**.

### Roman Numerals
**Definition**: Chord notation based on scale degrees. **Uppercase = major / lowercase = minor / Â° = diminished**.  
**Guitar Note**: Memorize progressions like **Iâ€“Vâ€“viâ€“IV** for instant transposition.  
**Example**: Iâ€“Vâ€“viâ€“IV in C â†’ **Dâ€“Aâ€“Bmâ€“G** in D.  
â†’ Learn more: [/resources/music-theory#roman](/resources/music-theory#roman)

---

## B. Chords and Symbols

### Root
**Definition**: The starting point of a chord.  
**Guitar Note**: When bass is present, **reduce root emphasis** and prioritize 3rd/7th for clarity.  
**Example**: In G7, let bass handle G, focus upper voices on **B (3rd) Â· F (7th)**.

### 3rd / 5th / 7th
**Definition**: 3rd = character, 5th = skeleton, 7th = directional arrow.  
**Guitar Note**: The essential formula for accompaniment is **never skip 3rd/7th**.  
**Example**: Voice lead **Bâ†’C** (3rdâ†’root from G7â†’C) in the top voice.

### Triad
**Definition**: Three-note chord built on 1Â·3Â·5.  
**Guitar Note**: Moving just the **3rd** changes the mood.  
**Example**: C â†’ **Cm** â†’ F (3rd moves Eâ†’Eâ™­).

### 7th Chord
**Definition**: Triad + 7th.  
**Guitar Note**: **V7 = strong resolution**, **maj7 = dissolves**.  
**Example**: G â†’ **G7** â†’ C / C â†’ **Cmaj7** â†’ C.

### sus / add / slash
**Definition**: **sus** suspends the 3rd, **add** adds notes, **slash** specifies bass note.  
**Guitar Note**: Sus creates "tension", slash enables **walking bass**.  
**Example**: Dâ€“**Dsus4**â€“D / Câ€“**C/E**â€“F.

### Inversion
**Definition**: Rearranging which chord tone is in the bass (lowest note).  
**Guitar Note**: Use **G/B, D/F#** etc. for smooth bass lines.  
**Example**: Câ†’**G/B**â†’Amâ†’**F/C**.

### Voicing
**Definition**: Internal arrangement of chord tones.  
**Guitar Note**: Design the **top note** to support the vocal melody.  
**Example**: Keep top notes **Eâ†’Eâ†’Fâ†’F** through Câ†’Amâ†’Fâ†’G.

### Form/Shape
**Definition**: Fingering pattern (Open/Barre, etc.).  
**Guitar Note**: Form â‰  voicing. **Same form with different arrangements** changes the feel.  
**Example**: C form with E on top vs. G on top sounds different.

---

## C. Progressions and Function

### T / S / D (Functional Harmony)
**Definition**: T = stable (I, vi), S = preparation (ii, IV), D = gravitational pull (V, viiÂ°).  
**Guitar Note**: **Tâ†’Sâ†’Dâ†’T** framework reduces confusion.  
**Example**: Cï½œFï½œGï½œC.  
â†’ Learn more: [/resources/music-theory#tsd](/resources/music-theory#tsd)

### Cadence
**Definition**: Resolution patterns (Vâ†’I / IVâ†’I / Vâ†’vi / etc.).  
**Guitar Note**: Use **Vâ†’I at chorus start** as a clear flag.  
**Example**: G7â†’C (authentic cadence).

### Secondary Dominant (V/â—‹â—‹)
**Definition**: Temporarily treat the target chord as tonic and approach with its V7.  
**Guitar Note**: **1â€“2 spot uses** create maximum impact.  
**Example**: In D, **E7â†’A** (V/Vâ†’V).  
â†’ Learn more: [/resources/music-theory#secondary](/resources/music-theory#secondary)

### Modal Interchange (Borrowed Chords)
**Definition**: Borrowing bVII, bVI, iv etc. from the parallel minor.  
**Guitar Note**: Works great with open strings. Adds a **sunset color**.  
**Example**: Dâ€“Câ€“G (Iâ€“bVIIâ€“IV).  
â†’ Learn more: [/resources/music-theory#modal-interchange](/resources/music-theory#modal-interchange)

### Tritone Substitution / Backdoor
**Definition**: V7â‡„bII7, or bVII7â†’I.  
**Guitar Note**: Use sparingly for rich color.  
**Example**: A7â†’D becomes **Eâ™­7â†’D**.  
â†’ Learn more: [/resources/music-theory#tritone-backdoor](/resources/music-theory#tritone-backdoor)

### Passing Diminished
**Definition**: Insert a chromatic bridge for just one beat.  
**Guitar Note**: Use **#ivoÂ°7** etc. for smooth transitions.  
**Example**: Dï½œ**G#Â°7**ï½œAï½œD.  
â†’ Learn more: [/resources/music-theory#diminished](/resources/music-theory#diminished)

---

## D. Extensions and Alterations

### 9/11/13 (Extensions)
**Definition**: Color tones above the 7th.  
**Guitar Note**: Add **just 1â€“2 targeted notes**.  
**Example**: Cmaj7(9), Am7(9,11).

### Alterations (â™­9 / â™¯9 / â™¯11 / â™­13)
**Definition**: Spices that shape dominant direction.  
**Guitar Note**: Align with chord tones of the resolution target.  
**Example**: G7(â™­9)â†’Cmaj7 / G7(â™¯11)â†’Cmaj7.

### Avoid Note
**Definition**: Notes that clash within a specific chord.  
**Guitar Note**: Watch for **11 over major** (half-step clash with 3rd).  
**Example**: F (11) on Cmaj7 needs careful handling.

---

## E. Practical Tips

### Harmonic Rhythm
**Definition**: Duration of chord changes.  
**Guitar Note**: Create **contrast** between sections.  
**Example**: Verse = 1 bar, chorus = 2 beats.

### Line ClichÃ©
**Definition**: Chromatic inner voice movement.  
**Guitar Note**: Iâ€“Imaj7â€“I7â€“IV is simple and effective.  
**Example**: Câ€“Cmaj7â€“C7â€“F.

### Pedal Point
**Definition**: Sustaining one note throughout changes.  
**Guitar Note**: Open string pedals are a guitar superpower.  
**Example**: Keep high strings open while changing chords below.

### Capo / Shaped / Sounding
**Definition**: **Shaped = finger positions, Sounding = actual pitches**.  
**Guitar Note**: **Decide key first, capo second**.  
**Example**: Match vocal with â€“2, then add Capo 2 to use C shapes.

---

